english:
  title: Reply to Jeon Yi-ji's Letter on Literary Theory
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: "On this day I bow my head before you, my friend. Long have we been parted, and my longing has grown deep. Suddenly I received your gracious letter of several pages, which I have held in my hands without setting it down. Your words shine not merely with beauty of expression, but your discussion of the strengths and weaknesses of literature is precise and cutting, striking at the very ailments of our age. How admirably you have held up the falling edifice of letters!\n\nYet you praise me beyond measure, even comparing me to Li Bai and Du Fu. How could I dare accept such words? You say that many in the world carelessly follow Su Shi and fail to reach his heights—these need not be mentioned. Even those few poets whose names ring true all follow Su Shi, not merely stealing his words but plundering his meanings to claim them as their own work. Only you, you say, do not tread the worn paths of the ancients but create language entirely anew, awakening people's eyes and ears in a way incomparable to poets of our time. Thus you elevate me to the clouds of heaven. Is this not excessive praise?\n\nYet what you call the creation of language and meaning—this is true. But this was not something I desired to do differently from the ancients; rather, circumstance forced my hand. Here is why: those who imitate the style of ancient poets must first study their works extensively, then can they follow and succeed. Otherwise, even plagiarism becomes difficult. Like a thief who must first spy out a rich man's house, learn its gates and walls and fences, and only then can he enter the chambers and steal his treasures undetected—otherwise he will be caught before reaching the treasure chest at all. Can one steal wealth without such preparation?\n\nI have been a wanderer since youth, lacking discipline in my studies. Though I have touched upon the Six Classics and histories, I have never plumbed their depths, much less mastered the commentaries of various schools. Not having thoroughly absorbed these works, how could I imitate their styles or steal their language? This is why I am forced to create new expressions.\n\nMoreover, scholars of our time first exhaust themselves with examination hall writings and have no leisure for the arts. Only after passing the examinations do they turn to poetry, and they become especially enamored with Su Shi. So each year, when the examination results are posted, people say, \"Thirty Su Shis have emerged again this year!\" These are the \"scattered voices\" you speak of. Some of these men do indeed approach Su Shi's mastery—but then they too are Su Shi, and should be honored accordingly. Why must you object so strongly?\n\nSu Shi is truly the grandest poet of recent centuries—his works are like the treasury of a wealthy man overflowing with gold and jade, coins and pearls beyond measure. Even if thieves make off with his riches, his store remains inexhaustible. What harm is there in theft from such abundance?\n\nConsider: Mencius did not equal Confucius, nor did Xunzi and Yangzi equal Mencius. Yet after Confucius, none truly matched him until Mencius came close through emulation. After Mencius, none matched him until Xunzi and Yangzi drew near. Thus posterity speaks of \"Confucius and Mencius\" or \"Mencius the eloquent, Xunzi the wise\"—all because they approached through imitation. These few poets of our time, though they may not greatly resemble Su Shi, have likewise approached him through study. Who knows but that future ages may rank them with Su Shi? Why do you reject them so harshly?\n\nYet surely your words spring from genuine conviction, not empty speech. Perhaps you praise me to provoke thought in men of this age. The ancient Li Ao once said: \"The language of the Six Classics shows no mutual imitation in their creation and expression. Thus he who reads the Spring and Autumn Annals reads as if the Book of Poetry had never existed; he who reads the Poetry reads as if the Book of Changes had never existed; he who reads the Changes reads as if the Book of Documents had never existed—as the mountains have Heng and Hua, and the waters have the Huai and Ji.\" \n\nThe Six Classics do not parade their eloquence; their aim is to discuss kingship and hegemony, to expound virtue, to speak of governance and custom, the roots of rise and fall, order and chaos. Though their themes might seem to echo one another, their differences are profound.\n\nToday's poetry, though it springs from the Mao Commentary tradition, has developed elaborate rules—matters of phonetic pattern, parallelism, rhyme schemes, and variations—all intended to achieve technical refinement. Yet these very constraints bind the spirit. How then can one both create new meaning and achieve ultimate subtlety, without borrowing the words already spoken by the ancients? What effort would that even require?\n\nLet us speak of poets since the establishment of regulated forms. In the Tang there were Chen Zi'ang, Li Bai, Du Fu, Li Han, Li Yong, Yang Jiong, Wang Bo, Lu Zhao'lin, and Luo Binwang—all vast and sweeping, pouring forth like the Yellow and Huai Rivers, the Ying and the seas—displaying their bold genius. Yet I have never heard of one who mechanically stripped the bones from his predecessor's work. Later came Han Yu, Huangfu Shi, Li Ao, Li Guan, Lu Wen, Lu Tong, Zhang Ji, Meng Jiao, and Liu Yuxi, Lyu Zongyuan, Yuan Zhen, and Bai Juyi—galloping in harness together, surveying the ages—yet I have not seen any of them butchering the flesh of Chen Zi'ang or Li and Du and Yang and Wang. In the Song came Wang Anshi, Sima Guang, Ouyang Xiu, Su Ziyou, Mei Shengyu, Huang Luzhi, and the brothers Su Zizhan—they too made thunder tremble and the moon split, shaking their age—yet did they imitate Han Yu or Huangfu Shi, or carve up Liu and Lu and Yuan and Bai? I see no such mutilation.\n\nYet each established his own tradition. Pear and tangerine have different flavors, yet each pleases the mouth. The reason collections grow larger is to benefit later students. Should all merely recycle the old, they would be mere duplicate copies, wasting paper and ink. This is why you treasure new meaning.\n\nBut the ancient poets, though creating new meanings, spoke with a matured language. They had steeped themselves in the Classics, histories, and hundred schools—the words of the sages—until these had become part of their very breath. When they composed, they gathered all resources, drawing from left and right, combining freely. So though poetry and prose differ, they are one in how language is deployed and words employed. How could their expression not be refined?\n\nI am otherwise. Having not saturated myself in the wisdom of the ancients, and ashamed to imitate ancient poets' forms, when necessity strikes or the moment of composition arrives, I find my resources parched. I must then create new language entirely. Thus my words often seem crude and awkward, worthy of laughter. The ancients created meaning without creating language; I create both meaning and language without shame. This is why many contemporary poets glare at me in rejection. How could I have known that you alone would praise me so warmly?\n\nAlas, in this age men are greatly confused. Even stolen goods, if they please the eye, are eagerly savored—who bothers to ask their origin? Yet perhaps a hundred generations hence, should someone like you arise to judge truth from falsehood, even the most skilled thief will be caught, and my crude words may be praised as your praise is given now. Your words will be vindicated in time."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Li Bai (701-762) and Du Fu (712-770) are considered the two greatest poets of the Tang Dynasty, exemplifying perfection in the art.
  - key: ''
    value: Su Shi (1037-1101), known as Su Dongpo (Su of the Eastern Slope), was a major Song Dynasty poet, painter, and statesman whose innovative style dominated literary circles for centuries.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Six Classics (Liujing) refer to the foundational texts of Chinese civilization: the Book of Changes, Book of Documents, Book of Poetry, Rites, Spring and Autumn Annals, and one other work depending on tradition.'
  - key: ''
    value: Li Ao was a Tang Dynasty writer and philosopher known for his literary criticism and ethical thought.
  - key: ''
    value: This discussion reflects the traditional East Asian literary debate between imitation of classical forms and innovation—a tension central to Korean and Chinese literary aesthetics.
